{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3d93add4-35b5-4cf8-960b-9fecd4396ff8","content":"## Likely Cause\n\n.NET MAUI's Android workload (in .NET 8+) **bundles its own Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17**. When your `JAVA_HOME` points to Temurin, it overrides the bundled JDK and can cause version-string parsing failures or tooling incompatibilities.\n\n## Fix Options\n\n**Option 1 — Unset JAVA_HOME** (let the workload use its bundled JDK):\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build -f net8.0-android\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Explicitly point the build at the bundled JDK** in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(HOME)/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_openjdk_17</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n(The exact path varies — run `dotnet android sdk info` or check `~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/` for the actual directory name.)\n\n**Option 3 — Remove the JAVA_HOME export** from your shell profile (`~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile`) so it never interferes with .NET builds.\n\n## TL;DR\n\nYou don't need a separate JDK for MAUI Android — the workload provides one. Remove or unset `JAVA_HOME` and the build should succeed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5928a58d-f91a-4fe5-9437-dcb37a69d64e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nThis is a common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds. The problem is likely that .NET MAUI / Android SDK requires a specific Java version, and the issue is often related to:\n\n1. .NET 8+ MAUI requires JDK 17, which they have\n2. But the common issue on macOS is that `JAVA_HOME` needs to point to the correct path structure\n\n\n3. There's also a conflict possibility: .NET 8's Android workload ships with Microsoft's OpenJDK 17, so having a different JDK installed could be causing interference with the build process. The bundled Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the .NET Android workload typically takes precedence over `JAVA_HOME`, but conflicts arise when they're mismatched or when one interferes with the other. On macOS specifically, installing Temurin JDK separately often creates this exact problem.\n\nThe real issue is likely that .NET 8+ MAUI requires JDK 17 from the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK bundled with the workload, and when `JAVA_HOME` points to Temurin instead, the build system can't properly parse the version string format, causing failures. Temurin-17.0.12+7 can cause issues with version parsing in older versions of the Android build tooling.\n\nLet me reconsider the actual root cause here. The most common Java problem with .NET MAUI Android builds is that when `JAVA_HOME` points to a non-Microsoft JDK, it can override the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17 that comes with .NET 8+, leading to compatibility issues. The solution is typically to unset `JAVA_HOME` entirely so the workload uses its bundled JDK, or explicitly configure `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the project file to point to the correct one. point to the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK\n\nBut without the actual error message, I should probably ask for clarification or go with the most likely culprit.\n\nActually, I think I know what this might be. Let me reconsider...\n\n**JDK 17.0.12 specifically** - is there a known issue with this version? I vaguely recall problems with newer JDK 17 patches and the Android Gradle plugin or d8/r8 tools, though I'm not certain about 17.0.12.\n\nLet me approach this differently. The user has:\n- macOS\n- .NET MAUI Android build failing\n- An unspecified Java error\n- Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12\n- JAVA_HOME pointing to it\n- java -version showing the correct version\n\nThe real issue is likely that **.NET's Android SDK bundles its own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK 17), and having JAVA_HOME set to Temurin creates a conflict.** The fix is either to unset JAVA_HOME and let the build use the bundled JDK, or to explicitly set `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the project file.\n\nThough on macOS with Apple Silicon, there's also the possibility of an architecture mismatch if an x64 JDK is installed on an ARM machine. But the bundled JDK conflict is the most common issue across the board.\n\nI'm leaning toward the answer that **.NET MAUI's Android workload in .NET 8+ ships with its own JDK**, which is the root cause here.","outputTokens":2159,"requestId":"A849:1D9368:65A1C5:755B9E:69FBE249"},"id":"61cd10d6-c79d-442a-9b2d-3ccda25ecf65","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:53:04.491Z","parentId":"c7aaccee-38be-4e43-b707-077ca17a483b"}
